For this week's assignment, I chose the Enron Dataset as prepared and collected by the CALO Project. It contains data surrounding 150 users, mostly senior management from the now defunct Enron. The whole corpus contains 517,000 emails and has been made available through the Federal Enery Regulatory Commission for public use. Many different fields use this dataset for training (both machine and personnel) and testing of word based algrothrims or programs.

For our purposes in the assignment, the analysis is focused in the email network documentation. The dataset includes 36,692 nodes with 183,831 edges and contains 367,662 points. According to the snap.Stanford.edu site, the total diameter is 11.

There seems to be key nodes the others connect to. This makes since as the data is based on a company's email, the nodes could the key players (Directors, VP's, C-level staff).

The next step should be defining which nodes are the key players and redrawing the graphic. By gaining the centrality metric we can see "the most important" nodes. The degree centrality works by assigning an importance score based simply on the number of links held by each node [1].

We will start by determining the "top" 10 nodes and seperating those values into a list.

In [12]:
sc = nx.communicability_centrality(G)
In [13]:
sorted_sc=sorted(sc.items(), key=itemgetter(1), reverse=True)
sorted_sc=sorted_sc[:10]
sorted_sc=pd.DataFrame(sorted_sc)
sorted_sc=sorted_sc[0]
sorted_sc=sorted_sc.values.tolist()

With the list, we will subset the orginial dataframe to only include nodes coming from these central nodes.

In [14]:
central_df=df[df.FromNode.isin(sorted_sc)]

I think there is much more we can dive into this data from a network prespective.

  • We can start breaking down twhich nodes which link these major nodes
  • Does any of these subnodes share commonality with other major nodes?
  • We can take each of the top nodes and break down the individual connections in each cluster, such as node 93.
